“From my observation, our context generates relatively few cases of women seeking help from police after a spouse has died,” said Ms. Idriss.

“Instead, many women tell us that their deceased husband’s families have attempted to take their businesses or assets for themselves. Married women in this country need strong legal protections that can protect them from the posthumous greed of others.”

Justice requires law, united families, and political will

Absent from previous debates about justice in Djibouti is the society’s pressing need to counteract the effects of poverty, discrimination and isolation that fuel high rates of violence against women.

According to sources on the ground and the United Nations, the country’s law on violence against women is partially functional, in that a broad list of violence is recognised as a crime, but enforcement of legal protections for women is extremely weak.

“This new law on violence is a first substantial step towards combating violence because it clearly lays out the acts and the punishment involved,” identified Fatouma Shawo, director of the local NGO Team for Development and Peace.

As an example of improving reality, Ms. Shawo cited the prosecution of a husband who killed his wife and threatened to burn their house down, when he could not face the repercussions of divorce.
